<font color="#FF0000">VFW AND THE COLONEL</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 17 12:19:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Gerald<br>
&gt;Many Vietnam Vets were treated like dirt at many a VFW or American Legion Post for years; because they &quot;lost&quot; the  war.&lt;<br><br>
Earlier, I had listed a few of negative events of my home coming.  Obviously, in this format, one's history needs to be abbreviated, thus much has to be left unsaid.  However, the quote above had brought to mind something that I would like to share for reasons I'll save for last.<br><br>
The Island of Oahu in Hawaii has many military bases.  Housing on base and off base were at a premium.  Officers as well as enlisted men took what ever was available.  About six months after my return, a colonel had moved next door with his family. He made attempts at small talk with me several times and I confirmed for him that I was a vet after his repeated prodding.  One day, he asked permission to sponser me for membership with the local VFW chapter.  My response was &quot;whatever&quot; and I left it at that.  A couple of weeks later, he had told me that the application was denied because the Vietnam war was not a declared war.  By that time, these kinds of things were not unexpected so it didn't surprise me, though, to this day, I have never joined any veteran organizations be it DAV, VFW, VVA, or such.  I wouldn't go out of my way to piss on a VFW building were it burning.  All the junkmail I get from these folks gets trashed.<br><br>
But the missed oppotunity here was not the incident with VFW, but with the colonel.  Here was one individual who had, knowing I was a Viet Nam vet, made advances at friendship or camaraderie and I had rebuffed him.  Wonder how would things had turned out had I embraced his gestures of friendship?  Though this does not fit in the purpose of this thread, I wanted to take seize the opportunity to honour this individual.  I'll refrain from such in the future.
